Under the optimized conditions, as the glucose concentrations increase, the fluorescent emission at 580 nm decreases, while the fluorescence emission of the oxVB1 at 450 nm increases (Fig. 4
                        A). The color of the fluorescence changed from red to blue (Fig. 4A inset). The ratio of I450/I580 exhibited a good linear correlation with H2O2 in 0.5–500 μM concentrations range, and the linear equation is I450/I580 = 0.0107CH2O2 - 0.1412 (R2 = 0.9930), with a low detection limit of 0.10 μM (S/N = 3) (Fig. 4B). In addition, the analysis of H2O2 can be implemented by measuring the absorbance of the C-dots, the absorption peak at 557 nm reduces with increasing H2O2 concentrations from 0 to 700 μM (Fig. 4C). The color of the C-dots changed from purplish-red to colorless (Fig. 4C inset). The absorbance is linearly correlated with H2O2 in the 0.5–200 μM concentrations range, and the linear equation is A557 = -0.0011CH2O2 + 0.3106 (R2 = 0.9918). The detection limit of colorimetric method is 2.44 μM (S/N = 3) (Fig. 4D). Overall, this ratiometric fluorescent and colorimetric sensing system can sensitively detect H2O2, with better performance compared with the reported methods (Table 1
                        ).

As shown in Fig. 5
                        A, as the glucose concentrations increase, the intensity of the fluorescent emission at 580 nm decreases, while the fluorescent emission of oxVB1 at 450 nm increases. Fig. S6 showed the CIE 1931 color diagram of glucose titration. With the addition of glucose, the fluorescent color changed from red to blue, which was consistent with the above-described phenomenon of fluorescence changes in the detection of H2O2. The ratio of I450/I580 is linearly correlated with glucose concentrations from 0.8–300 μM (R2 = 0.9918) (Fig. 5B). The linear equation is I450/I580 = 0.0078Cglucose −0.0241, with a low detection limit of 0.14 μM (S/N = 3). Moreover, as the glucose concentrations increases, the absorbance of C-dots at 557 nm decreases (Fig. 5C). The absorbance (A557) is linearly correlated to glucose concentrations from 5 to 120 μM (Fig. 5D). The linear equation is A557 = -0.0016Cglucose + 0.3182 (R2 = 0.9915), with the detection limit is 3.26 μM (S/N = 3). Therefore, the proposed sensing system can be used for quantitative determination of glucose, showing superior performances compared to reported methods (Table 2
                        )
